supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, 1-220. Adesto domine suplicacionibus

p.note: Top left corner, in red ink: D. B. IV. 5; below, National Library book label with the current signum, A229; bottom left corner, in ink: 50.
Dedication in Polish by Felix Biernacki to the countess von Engeström.

binding.p: Modern binding. Red leather over cardboard; a border of gilded leaves. 5 bands and endbands. , stamped in gold: Manuscrit du XVme Siècle; below: the current signum A 229; below: avez des miniatures.

history.provenance: An owner's note in a late medieval or early modern hand on states that the book belonged to a mademoyselle de cheurieres, probably Chevrières. Next to it, an owner's note in a different hand gives the name Marguerite de Bielzuiais, probably Beauvais.

The watermark on , added at rebinding, gives the name Wunnerlich (first initial(s) not visible); Piccard online identifies a similar watermark belonging to Johann Albrecht Wunnerlich, active in Hof 1746–1822 (see Piccard online). A line of Wunnerlichs appear as papermakers in Bavaria (Hof/Moschendorf) between and (see blogus).

A dedication in Polish on reveals that the manuscript was given to the countess von Engeström (Rosalie, née Drya-Chlapowska), wife of statesman Lars von Engeström (1751–1826), by Felix Biernacki, a friend of the von Engeström family, with gratitude for meetings in Stockholm and Warsaw.
The signa D. B. IV. 5 and 50 on have not been identified.
history.acquisition: The manuscript was part of the donation to the National Library of Lars von Engeström's personal library made in by von Engeström's grandson (see SBL).

note.p: The bifolium making up / has been incorrectly placed in the sequence; it should come after the bifolium making up / ; consequently, contains text from the rhymed prayer to the Holy Cross and the suffrages come in the incorrect order; they should begin with St Michael (), and continue with St Anthony (). An early modern hand has added signes-de-renvoi at the relevant places.
